      <h3>Florence Nightingale's contributions to modern nursing and health care</h3>
				<p>Born May 12, 1820, in Florence, Italy, to Frances Nightingale and William Shore Nightingale</p>

<p>Grew up in the family home in Lea Hurst in England with a classical education</p>

<p>Declared her calling by age 16 to serve others as a nurse</p>

<p>Enrolled as a nursing student at the Lutheran Hospital of Pastor Fliedner in Kaiserwerth, Germany, in 1844</p>

<p>Returned to London as a nurse in a Middlesex hospital for the chronically ill</p>

<p>Battled poor health, which has been attributed to her contracting "Crimean fever," and was bedridden by age 38 but remained an advocated for health care reform</p>

<p>Died at age 90 on August 13, 1910, at her home in London</p>
